rounds.response:
It’s turn 3 (2 turns already elapsed).  
Last turn Player 0 (me) offered 5 Sheep → 3 Brick and it was rejected.  
I can only guess at Player 1’s inventory, so let’s stay flexible.

Current value of my holdings  
- Sheep: 18×18 = 324  
- Brick: 5×29 = 145  
- Ore: 9×37 = 333  
- Wood: 13×10 = 130  
- Wheat: 8×5 = 40  
Total ~972

My goal: increase total value without giving away high-VP resources. Since Brick has the second-highest value (29 each) but I only own 5 of them, it’s the obvious surplus target. I was willing to overpay slightly (5 Sheep ≈ 5×18 = 90 for 3 Brick ≈ 3×29 = 87) to raise my Brick count, but Player 1 declined; they probably value Brick at least 30:1 or simply have enough Sheep.

Let’s try a lower-Sheep offer (less burdensome) and ask only for 2 Brick, which still boosts my Brick pool by 40 %. I’ll use Wood, which has low value for me (10), in the bundle to keep the Spectrum flexible.

[Offer: 3 Sheep, 2 Wood -> 2 Brick, 1 Sheep]

Looking at today’s market value per unit:

- Wheat 5  
- Wood 10  
- Sheep 18  
- Brick 29  
- Ore 37  

The numbers tell the story: I’m heavily stocked in low/mid-value resources (especially Sheep and Wood), but light on Brick and very light on Ore. Brick and Ore move the payoff needle fastest, so I’ll focus my offers on trying to pry more of them loose while still looking “fair” to the opponent.

Current inventory:
8 Wheat, 13 Wood, 18 Sheep, 5 Brick, 9 Ore.  
Total value ≈ 1 300

Ideal immediate swap profile:  
- Offer 2–3 surplus resources that the opponent may value more than Brick/Ore.  
- Target an addition of 1–2 Brick or Ore in every exchange.  

What the opponent rejected so far  
- Sheep-centric offers for Brick (twice).  
Helper insight: Player 1 may undervalue Sheep or already have plenty of them. So:
  – I won’t lead with Sheep again right away.  
  – Mix Wood or Wheat into the package instead.

Next move
I’ll try to entice Player 1 with Wood (a mid-value commodity) while still using some Sheep to sweeten the deal. The package below would immediately add 2 Brick to my stack, pushing my total value up by 20 while losing only one relatively low-value Wheat and three mid-value Wood:

rounds.response:
Let’s take stock of the turn-by-turn state.

Current turn: 5 (we’ve just finished accept/reject decisions)  
My present inventory:

- Wheat: 8  
- Wood: 13 – 2 + 0 = 11 (I accepted a trade giving away 2 Wood)  
- Sheep: 18 – 0 + 0 = 18 (no Sheep have changed yet)  
- Brick: 5 – 0 + 3 = 8 (I just received 3 Brick from Player 1)  
- Ore: 9 – 0 + 5 = 14 (I just received 5 Ore from Player 1)

Total instance values:
5 × 8 Wheat = 40  
10 × 11 Wood = 110  
18 × 18 Sheep = 324  
29 × 8 Brick = 232  
37 × 14 Ore = 518  
Total = 1224

Looking at the values, anything raises my total when the value-per-unit I receive exceeds what I give away. The biggest gaps in value/ unit among my holdings are:

- Wheat (5/ unit) and Wood (10/unit) are low.  
- Sheep (18/unit) and Ore (37/unit) are my highest.

Therefore I’m willing to trade my surplus Wheat/Wood for anything worth more than 5 for the former or 10 for the latter. Sheep and Ore I’m willing to part with only for a big overpay (bad deal for opponent) so I won’t propose giving any away.

I have excess Sheep (18) and would like still more Brick to unequivocally gain value since Brick is worth 29/unit.

Target offer calculation  
Meaningful surplus in hand:  
– Sheep: 18 (can easily spare 6-8)  
Goal: Maximize Brick (29) received while giving away the cheapest units.

Let’s offer 7 Sheep (value 126) for 3 Brick (value 87). Although this looks unfavorable for me in simple multiplication numbers, Brick’s marginal utility to me (I only have 8 and may need more for settlements) and eventual building needs may outweigh. Also 7 Sheep/3 Brick is reasonably close to the Catan ore/brick-port rate of 4-for-1.

[Offer: 7 Sheep -> 3 Brick]
